        <div class="floated-box float-left">Float Left</div>
        <div class="floated-box float-right">Float Right</div>
        <p>This paragraph will wrap around both floated boxes initially. However, the element below with `clear: both;` will ensure it starts on a new line, below both floats.</p>
        <p>More content here, flowing around the floats.</p>
        <div class="clearing-element">
            I have `clear: both;` applied. I will always appear below ALL preceding floated elements (left and right).
        </div>
        <p>Content after the clearing element will continue normally.</p>
    </div>

</body>
</html>
```

## Key Takeaways
*   **Purpose:** `clear` is used to prevent an element from appearing next to a floated element, forcing it to move below the float.
*   **Interaction with Floats:** It only works in conjunction with `float` properties (`float: left;` or `float: right;`).
*   **Values:** `left`, `right`, `both

## Quick Summary
A Block Formatting Context (BFC) is an independent rendering region within a web page. It defines how block-level boxes are laid out and interact with each other within that region, ensuring that the content inside a BFC doesn't visually overlap with content outside of it, and vice-versa.

## How It Works
Think of a BFC as a self-contained environment for layout. When an element establishes a BFC, it creates a "mini-layout" inside itself. Key behaviors of elements within a BFC include:

1.  **No Margin Collapse:** Adjacent block-level elements *within the same BFC* will have their vertical margins collapse. However, vertical margins between an element *inside* a BFC and an element *outside* the BFC (or between a BFC and its containing BFC) will *not* collapse.
2.  **Containing Floats:** A BFC will fully contain any floats within it. This means the BFC's background and border will wrap around its floated children, preventing them from "overflowing" out of the parent. This is a common way to clear floats without using an explicit `clear` property on a sibling element.
3.  **Preventing Overlap with Floats:** A BFC will not overlap with floats. If there's a float next to a block-level element that establishes a BFC, the BFC will shrink its width to make room for the float, rather than flowing under it.

**How to establish a BFC:**
Several CSS properties can create a BFC when applied to an element. Common ways include:

*   `overflow` property set to anything other than `visible` (e.g., `auto`, `scroll`, `hidden`). This is one of the most common and often used techniques.
*   `display` property set to `flow-root` (modern and explicit).
*   `display` property set to `inline-block`, `table-cell`, `table-caption`.
*   `position` property set to `absolute` or `fixed`.
*   `float` property set to anything other than `none`.

