## Quick Summary
`flex: 1` is a shorthand CSS property for flex items that sets `flex-grow: 1`, `flex-shrink: 1`, and `flex-basis: 0%`. It essentially tells a flex item to grow and shrink proportionally within the available space of its flex container, starting from a base size of 0.

## How It Works
When you apply `flex: 1` to a flex item, you're setting three individual flex properties:

1.  **`flex-grow: 1`**: This is the most impactful part. It specifies the "grow factor" of a flex item. If there's extra space in the flex container, items with `flex-grow` greater than 0 will expand to fill it. An item with `flex-grow: 1` will take up an equal share of the available positive free space compared to other items with `flex-grow: 1`. If one item has `flex-grow: 2` and another has `flex-grow: 1`, the first will take twice as much of the available space.
2.  **`flex-shrink: 1`**: This specifies the "shrink factor" of a flex item. If there isn't enough space in the flex container and items need to shrink, an item with `flex-shrink: 1` will shrink proportionally to its `flex-shrink` value relative to other items. A value of `1` means it can shrink if necessary.
3.  **`flex-basis: 0%`**: This sets the initial main size of the flex item before any available space is distributed. A `flex-basis` of `0%` means the item's content size is ignored initially; the item will start with a base size of 0 and then grow or shrink based on `flex-grow` and `flex-shrink` to fill the available space. This is often desired when you want flex items to distribute space purely based on their `flex-grow` values.

**Practical Example:**
Imagine a row of three boxes inside a flex container. If all three have `flex: 1`, they will each take up an equal one-third of the container's width, assuming enough space. If the container is too small, they will all shrink equally. If one box has `flex: 2` and the other two have `flex: 1`, the first box will take up twice as much space as the other two (e.g., 50%, 25%, 25%).

