## Quick Summary
No, `Array.prototype.sort()` is **not guaranteed to be stable** in JavaScript according to the ECMAScript specification. This means that for elements considered equal by the sorting function, their relative order in the sorted array might not be preserved from their original order.

## How It Works
A stable sort algorithm maintains the relative order of records with equal keys. If two elements, `a` and `b`, have the same sort key and `a` appears before `b` in the original array, then in a stable sort, `a` will still appear before `b` in the sorted array.

In JavaScript, the ECMAScript specification for `Array.prototype.sort()` states:
> "The sort is not necessarily stable. The default sort order is according to string conversions of the elements."

This means that different JavaScript engines (V8 in Chrome/Node.js, SpiderMonkey in Firefox, JavaScriptCore in Safari) are free to implement `sort()` using various algorithms (e.g., Timsort, Quicksort, Mergesort, Heapsort). While some engines *might* use a stable sort algorithm in certain circumstances (like Timsort, which is stable), you cannot rely on this behavior across all environments or even different versions of the same engine.

**Practical Example:**
Imagine sorting an array of objects where multiple objects have the same `age`. If you sort by `age`, and the `sort()` implementation is unstable, the original order of people with the same `age` might be shuffled.

```typescript
interface Person {
    name: string;
    age: number;
    id: number; // To track original order
}

const people: Person[] = [
    { name: "Alice", age: 30, id: 1 },
    { name: "Bob", age: 25, id: 2 },
    { name: "Charlie", age: 30, id: 3 }, // Same age as Alice, originally after Alice
    { name: "David", age: 25, id: 4 }, // Same age as Bob, originally after Bob
    { name: "Eve", age: 35, id: 5 },
];

// Sort by age
const sortedPeople = [...people].sort((a, b) => a.age - b.age);

console.log("Original Order:");
people.forEach(p => console.log(`  Name: ${p.name}, Age: ${p.age}, ID: ${p.id}`));

console.log("\nSorted Order (by age):");
sortedPeople.forEach(p => console.log(`  Name: ${p.name}, Age: ${p.age}, ID: ${p.id}`));

// Observe Alice (id:1) and Charlie (id:3) - both age 30.
// In an unstable sort, Charlie might appear before Alice, even though Alice was first in original.
// Observe Bob (id:2) and David (id:4) - both age 25.
// In an unstable sort, David might appear before Bob, even though Bob was first in original.
```
In the example above, if the sort were stable, Alice (id:1) would always appear before Charlie (id:3) in the sorted array, and Bob (id:2) before David (id:4), because they have the same age and that was their original relative order. Since it's not guaranteed stable, their relative order is unpredictable.

## Code Example
To achieve a stable sort when you need it, you typically augment the comparison function to include a secondary sort key that represents the original order. This is often done by adding an index to the objects before sorting.

```typescript
interface Item {
    value: number;
    originalIndex?: number; // Optional property to store original index
}

const data: Item[] = [
    { value: 10 },
    { value: 5 },
    { value: 10 }, // Duplicate value, originally after the first 10
    { value: 3 },
    { value: 5 },  // Duplicate value, originally after the first 5
];

// 1. Add original index to each item
const dataWithIndex: Item[] = data.map((item, index) => ({ ...item, originalIndex: index }));

console.log("Original data with indices:");
dataWithIndex.forEach(item => console.log(`  Value: ${item.value}, Original Index: ${item.originalIndex}`));

// 2. Perform a stable sort by primary value, then by original index for ties
const stableSortedData = [...dataWithIndex].sort((a, b) => {
    // Primary sort key: value
    if (a.value !== b.value) {
        return a.value - b.value;
    }
    // Secondary sort key for stability: originalIndex (if values are equal)
    // We can confidently use the non-null assertion '!' here because we added it above.
    return a.originalIndex! - b.originalIndex!;
});

console.log("\nStable Sorted data:");
stableSortedData.forEach(item => console.log(`  Value: ${item.value}, Original Index: ${item.originalIndex}`));

