## Quick Summary
The third parameter of `EventTarget.addEventListener()` is an optional argument that can be either a boolean or an object. It primarily controls two aspects: whether the event listener should be invoked during the capturing phase (when `true` or `{ capture: true }`), and various other options like whether the event is passive or fired only once.

## How It Works (with practical examples)

The third parameter determines how and when the event listener is invoked during the event propagation lifecycle.

1.  **Boolean `useCapture` (legacy syntax):**
    *   If `true`, the event listener will be triggered during the **capturing phase**. This means the event will be handled as it trickles down from the `window` to the target element.
    *   If `false` (default), the event listener will be triggered during the **bubbling phase**. This means the event will be handled as it bubbles up from the target element to the `window`.

    **Example:** Consider a `div` inside a `body`. If `body` has a capturing listener and `div` has a bubbling listener, the `body` listener fires first when clicking the `div`.

2.  **`options` object (modern syntax):**
    This provides more granular control and is the recommended way. It can contain the following properties:

    *   `capture`: A boolean. Same as the `useCapture` boolean parameter. If `true`, the listener is invoked in the capturing phase. Defaults to `false`.
    *   `once`: A boolean. If `true`, the listener will be invoked at most once, and then automatically removed. Useful for one-time actions. Defaults to `false`.
    *   `passive`: A boolean. If `true`, indicates that the listener will *not* call `preventDefault()`. This is particularly useful for scroll and touch events to improve scrolling performance, as it tells the browser it doesn't need to wait for the listener to complete before scrolling. Defaults to `false`.
    *   `signal`: An `AbortSignal`. Allows the listener to be removed using an `AbortController`. This is useful for managing multiple listeners or listeners tied to a component's lifecycle.

    **Example:** Setting a `click` listener that only fires once and is registered in the capturing phase.

## Code Example

```typescript
// Get references to elements
const grandParent = document.getElementById('grandparent');
const parent = document.getElementById('parent');
const child = document.getElementById('child');

// Helper to log events
function logEvent(elementId: string, phase: string, eventType: string) {
    console.log(`${elementId} - ${eventType} - ${phase}`);
}

// Example 1: Capturing vs. Bubbling (using boolean)
grandParent?.addEventListener('click', () => logEvent('Grandparent', 'Capturing (bool)', 'click'), true); // Capturing
parent?.addEventListener('click', () => logEvent('Parent', 'Bubbling (bool)', 'click'), false);       // Bubbling (default)
child?.addEventListener('click', () => logEvent('Child', 'Bubbling (bool)', 'click'));                // Bubbling (default)

// When you click the 'child' element, the output will be:
// Grandparent - click - Capturing (bool)
// Child - click - Bubbling (bool)
// Parent - click - Bubbling (bool)


// Example 2: Using the options object for more control

const button = document.getElementById('myButton');

// Listener that only fires once
button?.addEventListener('click', () => {
    console.log('This button was clicked only once!');
}, { once: true });

// Listener that uses capturing phase
button?.addEventListener('click', () => {
    console.log('This listener fires in the capturing phase.');
}, { capture: true });

// Listener for a scroll event that is passive (won't call preventDefault)
const scrollableDiv = document.getElementById('scrollableDiv');
scrollableDiv?.addEventListener('scroll', (event) => {
    console.log('Scroll event occurred (passive)');
    // event.preventDefault(); // This would log a warning in the console if passive is true
}, { passive: true });

// Example 3: AbortSignal to remove listeners programmatically
const abortButton = document.getElementById('abortButton');
const controller = new AbortController();

abortButton?.addEventListener('click', () => {
    console.log('Abort button clicked!');
    controller.abort(); // This will remove the 'onceOff' listener
});

const onceOff = document.getElementById('onceOff');
onceOff?.addEventListener('click', () => {
    console.log('This listener will be removed by AbortController');
}, { signal: controller.signal });

// After clicking 'abortButton', clicking 'onceOff' will no longer log.
