## Quick Summary
Both `async` and `defer` attributes on a `<script>` tag allow the browser to download external JavaScript files without blocking the HTML parsing. The key difference lies in when the script is executed: `async` scripts execute as soon as they are downloaded (potentially out of order), while `defer` scripts execute in the order they appear in the document, only after the HTML has been completely parsed but before the `DOMContentLoaded` event.

## How It Works
Traditionally, a `<script>` tag without `async` or `defer` blocks the HTML parser. The browser stops parsing, downloads the script, executes it, and then resumes parsing. This can significantly slow down page rendering.

**`async` attribute:**
- **Download:** The script is downloaded asynchronously in parallel with HTML parsing.
- **Execution:** The script executes as soon as it's available, interrupting HTML parsing if it's still ongoing.
- **Order:** Execution order is *not guaranteed*. If you have multiple `async` scripts, the one that finishes downloading first will execute first, regardless of its position in the HTML.
- **Use Case:** Ideal for independent scripts that don't rely on the DOM being fully ready or on other scripts' execution order, such as analytics scripts, ad scripts, or polyfills.

**`defer` attribute:**
- **Download:** The script is downloaded asynchronously in parallel with HTML parsing.
- **Execution:** The script executes only *after* the HTML document has been fully parsed (i.e., the DOM is ready), but *before* the `DOMContentLoaded` event fires.
- **Order:** Execution order *is guaranteed*. Deferred scripts will execute in the order they appear in the HTML.
- **Use Case:** Perfect for scripts that interact with the DOM or depend on the full HTML structure, such as UI manipulation scripts, application logic, or third-party libraries that need the DOM. It behaves somewhat like placing a regular `<script>` tag just before the closing `</body>` tag, but with the advantage of parallel download.

**Browser Support:** Both `async` and `defer` are widely supported in modern browsers.

## Code Example

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Async vs Defer Example</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Async vs Defer Scripts</h1>

    <p>This paragraph is parsed before any script execution (unless async interrupts).</p>

    <!--
        Async script: Downloads in parallel, executes as soon as ready.
        Execution order with other async scripts is not guaranteed.
        Might execute before the DOM is fully parsed.
    -->
    <script async src="async-script-1.js"></script>
    <script async src="async-script-2.js"></script>

    <!--
        Defer script: Downloads in parallel, executes AFTER HTML parsing is complete,
        but BEFORE DOMContentLoaded. Execution order is guaranteed.
    -->
    <script defer src="defer-script-1.js"></script>
    <script defer src="defer-script-2.js"></script>

    <p>This paragraph is also part of the HTML content.</p>

    <!-- Regular script: Blocks HTML parsing, downloads, executes, then parsing resumes. -->
    <script src="blocking-script.js"></script>

    <p>End of body content.</p>

    <script>
        // This inline script will execute after all defer scripts and blocking scripts
        // because it appears later in the document.
        console.log("Inline script executed.");
        document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
            console.log("DOMContentLoaded event fired.");
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

