## Quick Summary
`reset.css` aims to strip all browser default styling, providing a blank slate for developers. `Normalize.css`, on the other hand, makes browser styles consistent across different browsers while preserving useful defaults, fixing common bugs, and improving usability.

## How It Works (with practical examples)

### reset.css
A CSS reset removes all built-in browser styling for common elements (like `h1`, `p`, `ul`, `button`, etc.). This means that an `<h1>` tag will look exactly the same as a `<p>` tag by default – no bolding, no larger font size, no margins. The idea is to eliminate all inconsistencies and start from a completely predictable baseline.

**Pros:**
*   Complete control: You define every style from scratch.
*   Eliminates all browser differences for base elements.

**Cons:**
*   More CSS to write: You have to re-style *everything*, even basic things like bolding for `<strong>` or default list bullets.
*   Can make development slower for smaller projects.

### Normalize.css
Normalize.css doesn't remove styles; it standardizes them. It applies consistent, sensible default styles across all browsers. For example, it might ensure that `margin-bottom` on `h1` is the same in Chrome, Firefox, and Safari, or that `font-size` on `<pre>` elements behaves consistently. It also fixes common browser bugs (e.g., HTML5 elements not displaying correctly in old IE) and ensures elements like `sub` and `sup` behave as expected.

**Pros:**
*   Preserves useful browser defaults (e.g., `<h1>` is still larger and bold).
*   Fixes cross-browser inconsistencies and bugs.
*   Less CSS to write compared to a full reset, as you build upon a consistent base.
*   Improved accessibility by maintaining semantic defaults.

**Cons:**
*   Less "blank slate" control than a full reset, as some styles are preserved.

## Code Example

### Example of `reset.css` philosophy
(A simplified snippet demonstrating the aggressive reset approach)

```css
/* A very simplified reset.css snippet */
html, body, div, span, applet, object, iframe,
h1, h2, h3, h4, h5, h6, p, blockquote, pre,
a, abbr, acronym, address, big, cite, code,
del, dfn, em, img, ins, kbd, q, s, samp,
small, strike, strong, sub, sup, tt, var,
b, u, i, center,
dl, dt, dd, ol, ul, li,
fieldset, form, label, legend,
table, caption, tbody, tfoot, thead, tr, th, td,
article, aside, canvas, details, embed, 
figure, figcaption, footer, header, hgroup, 
menu, nav, output, ruby, section, summary,
time, mark, audio, video {
	margin: 0;
	padding: 0;
	border: 0;
	font-size: 100%;
	font: inherit;
	vertical-align: baseline;
}
/* HTML5 display-role reset for older browsers */
article, aside, details, figcaption, figure, 
footer, header, hgroup, menu, nav, section {
	display: block;
}
body {
	line-height: 1;
}
ol, ul {
	list-style: none;
}
blockquote, q {
	quotes: none;
}
blockquote:before, blockquote:after,
q:before, q:after {
	content: '';
	content: none;
}
table {
	border-collapse: collapse;
	border-spacing: 0;
}
```

### Example of `Normalize.css` philosophy
(A simplified snippet demonstrating the targeted normalization approach)

```css
/* A very simplified Normalize.css snippet */

/* Correct the line height in all browsers. */
html {
  line-height: 1.15;
  -webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%; /* Prevent adjustments of font size after orientation changes in iOS. */
}

/* Remove the margin in all browsers. */
body {
  margin: 0;
}

/* Render the `main` element consistently in IE. */
main {
  display: block;
}

/* Correct the font size and margin on `h1` elements within `section` and `article` contexts in Chrome, Firefox, and Safari. */
h1 {
  font-size: 2em; /* Keep default large font for h1 */
  margin: 0.67em 0; /* Standardize margin */
}

/* Remove the default padding on `ul` and `ol` elements in IE 10. */
ul, ol {
  padding: initial; /* Or apply a consistent padding */
}

/* Add the correct display in IE 10+. */
template {
  display: none;
}

/* Add the correct display in IE 10. */
[hidden] {
  display: none;
}
```

## Key Takeaways
*   **Reset.css:** Blanks the slate, removing all browser defaults for maximum control. Requires more custom CSS.
*   **Normalize.css:** Standardizes browser defaults

## Quick Summary
Client-side routing allows a web application to change the URL in the browser and update the displayed content without requesting a new HTML page from the server. This provides a faster, more responsive user experience, characteristic of Single-Page Applications (SPAs).

## How It Works
Client-side routing primarily leverages the browser's History API and JavaScript to manage navigation. Instead of the browser making a full page refresh request to the server when a link is clicked, the client-side router intercepts the navigation event, updates the URL, and then dynamically renders the appropriate UI component or view.

Here's a breakdown:

1.  **Intercepting Navigation:**
    *   When a user clicks on an internal link (e.g., `<a href="/about">About</a>`), the default browser behavior is to make a new HTTP request for `/about`.
    *   Client-side routers prevent this default behavior using `event.preventDefault()` on the click event.

2.  **Updating the URL:**
    *   The `History API` provides methods to manipulate the browser's session history.
    *   `history.pushState(state, title, url)`: Changes the URL in the address bar to `url` and adds an entry to the browser's history stack, allowing the back/forward buttons to work. It doesn't trigger a full page reload.
    *   `history.replaceState(state, title, url)`: Similar to `pushState`, but it replaces the current history entry instead of adding a new one. Useful for redirects.
    *   The `state` object can store any serializable data associated with the new history entry.

3.  **Listening for URL Changes:**
    *   The router listens for changes to the URL. This happens in two main scenarios:
        *   **Programmatic changes:** After `pushState` or `replaceState` is called.
        *   **Browser navigation:** When the user clicks the browser's back/forward buttons, the `popstate` event is fired. The router listens for this event to react to history changes.

4.  **Rendering the Correct View:**
    *   Based on the new URL path, the router determines which component or view should be displayed.
    *   It uses a routing configuration (e.g., a map of paths to components) to match the URL to the corresponding UI.
    *   JavaScript then dynamically updates the DOM to render the new content, often by hiding the old view and showing the new one, or by re-rendering a root component with new data.

**Practical Example:**
Imagine a simple SPA with routes `/`, `/about`, and `/contact`.
When a user clicks a link to `/about`:
1.  The click event is intercepted.
2.  `history.pushState({}, '', '/about')` is called, changing the URL.
3.  The router detects the URL change to `/about`.
4.  It renders the `AboutComponent` into a designated area of the page (e.g., a `div` with `id="app-root"`).

## Code Example

This is a simplified, vanilla JavaScript example to illustrate the core concepts. Real-world routers (like React Router, Vue Router, Angular Router) are far more sophisticated.

```typescript
// Define our routes and their corresponding content/components
const routes = {
  '/': '<h1>Home Page</h1><p>Welcome to the SPA!</p>',
  '/about': '<h1>About Us</h1><p>Learn more about our company.</p>',
  '/contact': '<h1>Contact Page</h1><p>Reach out to us!</p>',
  '/404': '<h1>404 - Not Found</h1><p>The page you requested does not exist.</p>'
};

// Function to render content based on the current path
const renderContent = (path: string) => {
  const appRoot = document.getElementById('app-root');
  if (appRoot) {
    appRoot.innerHTML = routes[path] || routes['/404'];
  }
};

// Handle navigation: prevent default link behavior, update URL, and render
const navigate = (event: Event) => {
  const target = event.target as HTMLAnchorElement;
  if (target && target.matches('a[data-route]')) { // Only handle links with data-route attribute
    event.preventDefault(); // Stop the browser from doing a full page reload
    const path = target.getAttribute('href')!;

    // Update the URL without a full page reload
    // pushState adds a new entry to the history
    window.history.pushState({}, '', path);

    // Render the new content
    renderContent(path);
  }
};

// Listen for browser back/forward button clicks (popstate event)
window.addEventListener('popstate', () => {
  renderContent(window.location.pathname);
});

// Initial render when the page loads
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  document.body.addEventListener('click', navigate); // Attach click listener to body for delegation
  renderContent(window.location.pathname); // Render content for the initial URL
});

