Improving performance in React applications is crucial for a smooth user experience. It often involves optimizing rendering cycles, reducing bundle size, and ensuring efficient data management.

## Quick Summary
React performance can be significantly improved by minimizing unnecessary re-renders using `React.memo`, `useMemo`, and `useCallback`, optimizing component structure to reduce the render tree, and leveraging tools like code splitting and virtualization for large datasets.

## How It Works (with practical examples)

### 1. Memoization
Memoization is a key technique to prevent unnecessary re-renders of components or re-computations of values/functions.

*   **`React.memo` (for functional components):** Higher-order component that memoizes a functional component. It re-renders only if its props have changed.

    ```typescript
    // Before: Renders every time ParentComponent renders
    const MyComponent = ({ value, onClick }) => {
      console.log('MyComponent rendered');
      return <button onClick={onClick}>{value}</button>;
    };

    // After: Renders only if 'value' or 'onClick' props change
    const MyMemoizedComponent = React.memo(({ value, onClick }) => {
      console.log('MyMemoizedComponent rendered');
      return <button onClick={onClick}>{value}</button>;
    });

    const ParentComponent = () => {
      const [count, setCount] = React.useState(0);
      const handleClick = () => console.log('Button clicked'); // This function reference changes on every render

      return (
        <div>
          <button onClick={() => setCount(c => c + 1)}>Parent Count: {count}</button>
          {/* Even if count changes, MyMemoizedComponent might re-render if its props are not stable */}
          <MyMemoizedComponent value="Click Me" onClick={handleClick} />
        </div>
      );
    };
    ```

*   **`useMemo` (for values):** Memoizes the result of a function. It re-computes the value only when one of its dependencies changes. Useful for expensive calculations.

    ```typescript
    const MyComponent = ({ list }) => {
      // Before: 'filteredList' is re-calculated on every render
      // const filteredList = list.filter(item => item.isActive);

      // After: 'filteredList' is re-calculated only if 'list' changes
      const filteredList = React.useMemo(() => {
        console.log('Filtering list...');
        return list.filter(item => item.isActive);
      }, [list]);

      return (
        <ul>
          {filteredList.map(item => (
            <li key={item.id}>{item.name}</li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      );
    };
    ```

*   **`useCallback` (for functions):** Memoizes a function instance. It returns the same function instance across re-renders unless its dependencies change. Crucial when passing callbacks to memoized child components.

    ```typescript
    const ParentComponent = () => {
      const [count, setCount] = React.useState(0);

      // Before: 'handleClick' is a new function on every render, causing MyMemoizedComponent to re-render
      // const handleClick = () => console.log('Button clicked');

      // After: 'handleClick' function reference is stable across renders (unless 'count' changes)
      const handleClick = React.useCallback(() => {
        console.log('Button clicked, count:', count);
      }, [count]); // Dependency array: if count changes, a new function is created

      return (
        <div>
          <button onClick={() => setCount(c => c + 1)}>Increment Parent Count: {count}</button>
          <MyMemoizedComponent value="Click Me" onClick={handleClick} />
        </div>
      );
    };
    ```

### 2. Code Splitting / Lazy Loading
Reduces the initial bundle size by loading only the necessary code for the current view.

*   **`React.lazy` and `Suspense`:**
    ```typescript
    import React, { Suspense } from 'react';

    // Before: All components are bundled together
    // import HeavyComponent from './HeavyComponent';

    // After: HeavyComponent is loaded only when needed
    const HeavyComponent = React.lazy(() => import('./HeavyComponent'));

    const App = () => (
      <div>
        <h1>Welcome</h1>
        <Suspense fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>
          <HeavyComponent />
        </Suspense>
