Let's break down the pros and cons of Node.js.

## Quick Summary
Node.js is a powerful JavaScript runtime built on Chrome's V8 engine, allowing developers to use JavaScript for both frontend and backend development. Its non-blocking, event-driven architecture makes it highly efficient for I/O-bound operations and real-time applications, but it can struggle with CPU-intensive tasks.

## How It Works (with practical examples)
Node.js operates on a single-threaded, event-loop model. When an I/O operation (like a database query or file read) is initiated, Node.js doesn't wait for it to complete. Instead, it offloads the operation to the system kernel and continues processing other requests. Once the I/O operation is finished, the kernel places its result in the event queue, and the event loop picks it up and executes the corresponding callback. This non-blocking nature is key to its performance.

**Example Scenario:** Imagine a web server handling multiple client requests simultaneously.

```typescript
import http from 'http';
import fs from 'fs';

const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
  if (req.url === '/') {
    res.writeHead(200, { 'Content-Type': 'text/plain' });
    res.end('Hello World!\n');
  } else if (req.url === '/readfile') {
    // This is a non-blocking I/O operation
    fs.readFile('./example.txt', 'utf8', (err, data) => {
      if (err) {
        res.writeHead(500, { 'Content-Type': 'text/plain' });
        res.end('Error reading file.');
        return;
      }
      res.writeHead(200, { 'Content-Type': 'text/plain' });
      res.end(`File content: ${data}\n`);
    });
  } else {
    res.writeHead(404, { 'Content-Type': 'text/plain' });
    res.end('Not Found\n');
  }
});

server.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log('Server running on port 3000');
});

// Create example.txt for the demo
