## Quick Summary
`block` and `inline` are fundamental `display` property values in CSS that define how an element behaves in terms of layout. Block-level elements take up the full available width and stack vertically, while inline-level elements only take up as much width as necessary and flow horizontally within the text content.

## How It Works (with practical examples)

### Block-level Elements
Block-level elements are like bricks in a wall: they stack on top of each other and take up the entire width of their parent container by default.

**Characteristics:**
*   **Takes full width:** Occupies 100% of the available width, pushing other elements to the next line.
*   **Starts on a new line:** Always begins on a new line.
*   **Height and width can be set:** `width`, `height`, `margin-top`, `margin-bottom`, `padding-top`, and `padding-bottom` properties all apply and affect the element's dimensions and spacing.
*   **Examples:** `<div>`, `<p>`, `<h1>` through `<h6>`, `<ul>`, `<li>`, `<form>`, `<header>`, `<footer>`, `<section>`.

**Practical Example:**
Imagine a series of paragraphs. Each paragraph is a block element, so even if it only has a few words, it will take up its own line and full width.

```html
<p>This is the first paragraph.</p>
<p>This is the second paragraph, showing how block elements stack vertically.</p>
```

### Inline-level Elements
Inline-level elements are like words in a sentence: they flow horizontally, only taking up the space they need, and don't force new lines.

**Characteristics:**
*   **Takes only necessary width:** Occupies only the width required by its content.
*   **Does not start on a new line:** Flows alongside other inline or text content.
*   **Limited box model control:** `width` and `height` properties are ignored. `margin-top` and `margin-bottom` are ignored (though `padding-top` and `padding-bottom` will increase the element's visual size, they won't affect the layout of surrounding elements). `margin-left`, `margin-right`, `padding-left`, and `padding-right` apply normally.
*   **Examples:** `<span>`, `<a>`, `<strong>`, `<em>`, `<img>`, `<input>`, `<label>`, `<button>`.

**Practical Example:**
Consider a sentence where some words are emphasized. The emphasized words are inline and don't break the sentence flow.

```html
This is a sentence with some <strong>important words</strong> and a <a href="#">link</a> within the flow.
```

