## Quick Summary
Prototypal inheritance is the mechanism in JavaScript where objects can inherit properties and methods from other objects. Instead of classes, JavaScript uses prototypes, meaning every object has a prototype from which it can inherit, forming a "prototype chain."

## How It Works
In JavaScript, every object has an internal slot called `[[Prototype]]` (exposed via `__proto__` or `Object.getPrototypeOf()`) that points to another object, its prototype. When you try to access a property or method on an object, JavaScript first checks if the property exists directly on that object. If not, it looks for the property on the object's prototype. If still not found, it continues up the prototype chain until it either finds the property or reaches `null` (the end of the chain).

This chain allows objects to share common functionality. When you create an object literal, its prototype is `Object.prototype`. When you create an object using a constructor function with `new`, the new object's prototype is set to the constructor's `prototype` property.

**Practical Example:**
Imagine we have a `Person` object. We want a `Developer` object to have all properties of `Person` (like `name`) but also its own specific properties (like `skills`) and methods. Instead of copying properties, `Developer` can simply inherit from `Person`'s prototype.

```typescript
// Define a base object (its prototype will be Object.prototype)
const person = {
  name: 'Alice',
  greet() {
    console.log(`Hello, my name is ${this.name}`);
  }
};

// Create another object, and make its prototype 'person'
// This is one way to link prototypes directly (Object.create)
const developer = Object.create(person);
developer.name = 'Bob'; // Overrides 'name' for developer, but 'person' still exists
developer.skills = ['JavaScript', 'TypeScript'];
developer.code = function() {
  console.log(`${this.name} is coding with ${this.skills.join(', ')}.`);
};

developer.greet(); // Output: Hello, my name is Bob (developer has greet via prototypal inheritance from person)
developer.code();  // Output: Bob is coding with JavaScript, TypeScript.

console.log(Object.getPrototypeOf(developer) === person); // true
console.log(Object.getPrototypeOf(person) === Object.prototype); // true
console.log(Object.getPrototypeOf(Object.prototype)); // null (end of the chain)

// When developer.greet() is called:
// 1. JavaScript looks for 'greet' on 'developer'. Not found.
// 2. JavaScript looks for 'greet' on 'developer's prototype (which is 'person'). Found!
// 3. The 'greet' method from 'person' is executed, with 'this' bound to 'developer'.
```

## Code Example (using Constructor Functions for a more common scenario)

```typescript
// 1. Constructor function for a base type
function Animal(name: string) {
  this.name = name;
}

// 2. Add a method to Animal's prototype
// All objects created with 'new Animal()' will inherit this method
Animal.prototype.makeSound = function() {
  console.log(`${this.name} makes a generic sound.`);
};

// 3. Constructor function for a more specific type
function Dog(name: string, breed: string) {
  // Call the parent constructor to inherit properties
  Animal.call(this, name); 
  this.breed = breed;
}

// 4. Set Dog's prototype to an object that inherits from Animal's prototype
// This establishes the prototype chain: dogInstance -> Dog.prototype -> Animal.prototype -> Object.prototype
Dog.prototype = Object.create(Animal.prototype);

// IMPORTANT: After overwriting Dog.prototype, reset the constructor property
Dog.prototype.constructor = Dog;

// 5. Add a method specific to Dog's prototype
Dog.prototype.bark = function() {
  console.log(`${this.name} the ${this.breed} barks! Woof!`);
};

// 6. Create instances
const genericAnimal = new Animal('Leo');
genericAnimal.makeSound(); // Output: Leo makes a generic sound.

const myDog = new Dog('Buddy', 'Golden Retriever');
myDog.makeSound(); // Output: Buddy makes a generic sound. (Inherited from Animal.prototype)
myDog.bark();      // Output: Buddy the Golden Retriever barks! Woof! (Specific to Dog.prototype)

console.log(myDog.name);   // Buddy (inherited property via Animal.call)
console.log(myDog.breed);  // Golden Retriever (Dog specific property)

// Verify the prototype chain
console.log(Object.getPrototypeOf(myDog) === Dog.prototype); // true
console.log(Object.getPrototypeOf(Dog.prototype) === Animal.prototype); // true
console.log(Object.getPrototypeOf(Animal.prototype) === Object.prototype); // true
```

## Key Takeaways
*   **Object-centric:** Unlike class-based inheritance, prototypal inheritance is about objects inheriting directly from other objects.
*   **Prototype Chain:** When a property/method is accessed, JavaScript traverses a chain of `[[Prototype]]` links until it finds the property or reaches `null`.
